---
import DocsLayout from '../../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';
import {karangoSidebar} from '../../../data/karango-sidebar';
import {Code} from 'astro:components';
---

<DocsLayout title="Entity Model" sidebar={karangoSidebar}
            description="Storable, Stored, New, Ref, and LazyRef — how Karango wraps your data for persistence">

    <h1>Entity Model</h1>

    <p class="text-xl text-gray-400 !mt-2 !mb-8">
        Any Kotlin data class can become a database entity. Karango wraps it with metadata (IDs, revisions)
        using the <code>Storable&lt;T&gt;</code> hierarchy — your data stays clean, the database details live in the
        wrapper.
    </p>

    <h2>The core idea</h2>

    <p>Your data class is just data. ArangoDB metadata (<code>_id</code>, <code>_key</code>, <code>_rev</code>) lives in
        the wrapper, not in your class:</p>

    <Code code={`// Your data — no database concerns
@Vault
data class Person(val name: String, val age: Int)

// After inserting into ArangoDB:
val stored: Stored<Person> = repo.insert(Person("Alice", 30))

stored.value  // Person(name="Alice", age=30) — your data
stored._id    // "persons/abc123" — database ID
stored._key   // "abc123" — document key
stored._rev   // "_abc123def" — revision for optimistic locking`} lang="kotlin" theme="vitesse-dark"/>

    <h2>The Storable hierarchy</h2>

    <p><code>Storable&lt;T&gt;</code> is the sealed base class. Four concrete types represent different entity states:
    </p>

    <div class="not-prose my-8">
        <table class="w-full text-sm text-left">
            <thead>
            <tr>
                <th class="px-3 py-2 border border-white/10 bg-white/[0.03] text-white font-semibold">Type</th>
                <th class="px-3 py-2 border border-white/10 bg-white/[0.03] text-white font-semibold">When to use</th>
                <th class="px-3 py-2 border border-white/10 bg-white/[0.03] text-white font-semibold">Has value?</th>
                <th class="px-3 py-2 border border-white/10 bg-white/[0.03] text-white font-semibold">Has ID?</th>
            </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody class="text-gray-400">
            <tr>
                <td class="px-3 py-2 border border-white/10"><code>New&lt;T&gt;</code></td>
                <td class="px-3 py-2 border border-white/10">Entity not yet persisted</td>
                <td class="px-3 py-2 border border-white/10">Yes</td>
                <td class="px-3 py-2 border border-white/10">Empty until inserted</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td class="px-3 py-2 border border-white/10"><code>Stored&lt;T&gt;</code></td>
                <td class="px-3 py-2 border border-white/10">Entity loaded from or saved to the database</td>
                <td class="px-3 py-2 border border-white/10">Yes</td>
                <td class="px-3 py-2 border border-white/10">Yes (_id, _key, _rev)</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td class="px-3 py-2 border border-white/10"><code>Ref&lt;T&gt;</code></td>
                <td class="px-3 py-2 border border-white/10">Reference to another entity (eagerly loaded)</td>
                <td class="px-3 py-2 border border-white/10">Yes</td>
                <td class="px-3 py-2 border border-white/10">Yes</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td class="px-3 py-2 border border-white/10"><code>LazyRef&lt;T&gt;</code></td>
                <td class="px-3 py-2 border border-white/10">Reference loaded on first access</td>
                <td class="px-3 py-2 border border-white/10">Lazy</td>
                <td class="px-3 py-2 border border-white/10">Yes (value loaded on demand)</td>
            </tr>
            </tbody>
        </table>
    </div>

    <h2>New&lt;T&gt; — entities before persistence</h2>

    <Code code={`// Wrap your data for explicit insertion
val newPerson = New(Person("Alice", 30))

// Or just pass the value directly — insert() wraps it for you
repo.insert(Person("Alice", 30))

// With an explicit key
repo.insert("alice-key", Person("Alice", 30))`} lang="kotlin" theme="vitesse-dark"/>

    <h2>Stored&lt;T&gt; — the main entity wrapper</h2>

    <p><code>Stored&lt;T&gt;</code> is what you work with most. It wraps your data with database metadata:</p>

    <Code code={`val stored: Stored<Person> = repo.findById("persons/abc123")!!

// Access data
stored.value.name  // "Alice"
stored.value.age   // 30

// Access metadata
stored._id         // "persons/abc123"
stored._key        // "abc123"
stored._rev        // revision string
stored.collection  // "persons"

// Modify the value — creates a new Stored with the same metadata
val updated = stored.modify { it.copy(age = 31) }
// updated._id is still "persons/abc123"

// Or use withValue for a direct replacement
val replaced = stored.withValue(Person("Bob", 25))`} lang="kotlin" theme="vitesse-dark"/>

    <h3>Modify and save pattern</h3>

    <Code code={`// Load → modify → save
val person = repo.findById(id)!!

val updated = person.modify { it.copy(name = "Alice Smith") }

repo.save(updated)`} lang="kotlin" theme="vitesse-dark"/>

    <h2>Ref&lt;T&gt; — eager entity references</h2>

    <p>A <code>Ref&lt;T&gt;</code> points to another entity by ID. The value is loaded eagerly:</p>

    <Code code={`@Vault
data class Comment(
    val text: String,
    val author: Ref<Person>,  // Reference to a Person
)

// The Ref has both the ID and the loaded value
val comment: Stored<Comment> = repo.findById(commentId)!!
comment.value.author._id     // "persons/abc123"
comment.value.author.value   // Person(name="Alice", age=30)`} lang="kotlin" theme="vitesse-dark"/>

    <p>When serialized to ArangoDB, <code>Ref&lt;T&gt;</code> is stored as just the ID string. When deserialized, the
        entity is loaded from the cache or database.</p>

    <h2>LazyRef&lt;T&gt; — lazy entity references</h2>

    <p>Like <code>Ref&lt;T&gt;</code> but the referenced entity is only loaded when first accessed:</p>

    <Code code={`@Vault
data class BlogPost(
    val title: String,
    val author: LazyRef<Person>,  // Only loaded when accessed
)

val post: Stored<BlogPost> = repo.findById(postId)!!
// author not loaded yet

post.value.author._id    // "persons/abc123" — available immediately
post.value.author.value  // Person(...) — NOW the entity is loaded`} lang="kotlin" theme="vitesse-dark"/>

    <h2>Converting between types</h2>

    <Code code={`val stored: Stored<Person> = repo.findById(id)!!

// Stored → Ref
val ref: Ref<Person> = stored.asRef

// Stored → LazyRef
val lazyRef: LazyRef<Person> = stored.asLazyRef

// Any Storable → Stored
val backToStored: Stored<Person> = ref.asStored`} lang="kotlin" theme="vitesse-dark"/>

    <h2>Identity comparisons</h2>

    <Code code={`val a: Stored<Person> = repo.findById("id1")!!
val b: Stored<Person> = repo.findById("id2")!!

a hasSameIdAs b    // false — different IDs
a hasOtherIdThan b // true

val list = listOf(a, b)
a hasIdIn list     // true`} lang="kotlin" theme="vitesse-dark"/>

    <h2>Type-safe casting</h2>

    <Code code={`sealed class Animal {
    data class Dog(val name: String) : Animal()
    data class Cat(val name: String) : Animal()
}

val stored: Stored<Animal> = repo.findById(id)!!

// Safe downcast — returns null if the type doesn't match
val dog: Stored<Dog>? = stored.castTyped<Dog>()
val cat: Stored<Cat>? = stored.castTyped<Cat>()`} lang="kotlin" theme="vitesse-dark"/>

    <div class="not-prose mt-8 flex gap-4">
        <a href="/ultra/karango/query-dsl"
           class="inline-flex items-center px-6 py-3 bg-brand-600 text-white font-semibold rounded-lg hover:bg-brand-500 transition-colors">
            Query DSL &rarr;
        </a>
    </div>

</DocsLayout>
